Requirement:  Create a security group under default VPC with 2 rules: 
1. Inbound rule of type HTTP, with port range of 80. Enter the source CIDR range of 0.0.0.0/0.
2. Inbound rule of type SSH, with port range of 22. Enter the source CIDR range of 0.0.0.0/0.

==================
LET'S TINKER
==================
Security Group is stateful firewall; that means it monitors the state of active connections. Unlike stateless firewalls (for example, NACL) that inspect each packet individually, stateful firewalls maintain a state table of established connections and use this context to make more intelligent decisions about whether to allow or block incoming and outgoing traffic. This allows them to provide a higher level of security and context-aware filtering. 

There are two approach for creating a security group. We will explore both ways one by one:

----------------------------------------
Creating security group from AWS console
----------------------------------------
1. Go to EC2->Security Groups  or  vpc->Security Groups
2. Click on Create security group
3. Fill the security group name and description
4. Choose the VPC from dropdown (In our case default VPC)
5. Add the inbound rules as per requirement.
6. Optional: Provide a tag to personalize if you are considering it as part of any personal project and make it easily identifiable for any automation pipeline.
7. Click on Create security group at the bottom.

--------------------------------------
Create security group from AWS CLI/SDK
--------------------------------------
> Get default VPC Id :  aws ec2 describe-vpcs --region us-east-1 --filters Name=is-default,Values=true --query "Vpcs[*].VpcId"
> Create security group : aws ec2 create-security-group --description "Test security group" --group-name test-sg region us-east-1 --vpc-id {{ vpc_id }}
> Describe security group: aws ec2 describe-security-groups --group-ids {{ security group id }} --region us-east-1
> Create http inbound rule: aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress --group-id {{ security group id }} --protocol tcp --port 80 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0 --region us-east-1
> Create ssh inbound rule: aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress --group-id {{ security group id }} --protocol tcp --port 22 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0 --region us-east-1
> Delete security group: aws ec2 delete-security-group --group-id {{ security group id }} --region us-east-1 
or,  aws ec2 delete-security-group --group-name {{ security group name }} --region us-east-1
